rmk:
Recorded:

  • alarm or scolding call, quickquickquickquick..., at 0:01.4, 0:05, 0:08.8 and 0:13.8

General observations: Alpine moor with minor bogs, close to a mountain lake. Whimbrel calls while flying short distances following the recordist. Temperature: 18°C/64.4 °F. Westerly wind, moderate breeze.

Recording remarks: At breeding ground the alarm call and low-whistle flight call is both often heard. The alarm call is commonly longer and less evenly pitched, compare with e.g. XC664128.

Other distinguishable species:

  • Meadow Pipit, Anthus pratensis, alarm call, sitt, at 0:03.2 (vaguely); flight call, ist ist, at 0:16.3 (vaguely)
  • Common Redshank, Tringa totanus, alarm or chip call, tyuk or chip, at 0:06.3 (vaguely)

Sound classification and rendering: NatureGuides, 2020, Birds of Western Palearctic, AppStore.

Recording equipment: Dodotronic Hi-sound Stereo AOL Parabolic Microphone, Sony PCM-A10 Recorder.

Recorded:

  • low-whistle call, püpüpÿpÿpüpüpü, at 0:01.7 and 0:11.1

General observations: Alpine moor with minor bogs, close to a mountain lake. Whimbrel calls while flying. Temperature: 18°C/64.4 °F. No wind.

Recording remarks: At breeding ground the low-whistle flight call and alarm call is both often heard. The low-whistle flight call is commonly shorter and more evenly pitched, compare with e.g. XC664129.

Other distinguishable species:

  • Common Redshank, Tringa totanus, alarm or chip call, tyuk or chip, at 0:04.4 (vaguely)
  • European Golden Plover, Pluvialis apricaria, alarm call, püüh, at e.g. 0:03.6
  • Arctic Tern, Sterna paradisaea, advertising call, kree-ah, e.g. at 0:04.2; juvenile begging call, at 0:05.1

Sound classification and rendering: NatureGuides, 2020, Birds of Western Palearctic, AppStore; Svensson, Mullarney and Zetterström, 2009, Collins Bird Guide, Second Edition, HarperCollinsPublishers.

Recording equipment: Dodotronic Hi-sound Stereo AOL Parabolic Microphone, Sony PCM-A10 Recorder.

rmk: Call note of bird on the ground being approached by a fisherman

The sheer panic that preceded this recording is part of the excitement of unexpectedly being in the right place at the right time - provided you can lay your hands on a sound recorder. I was on Inishbofin, west of Co. Galway, indoors on a calm August night but the cottage windows were open. I heard Whimbrels calling from in the night sky. Whimbrels are very common on Inishbofin in spring but quite scarce in autumn (when migrants take an overseas route from Iceland to Africa). I managed to grab my recorder and dash outside in time to capture the sound of several birds (I never saw them) passing south. It was a cloudy, moon-less night: possibly this is why the birds drifted in from the sea and hit the far west of Ireland?

This is the second recording of one of two Steppe Whimbrels N p alboaxillaris found in Maputo Bay, Mozambique in February 2016. There are many photos available of these birds. This bird is thought to be a male and this bubbling call was recorded as part of a dispute with an adjacent Whimbrel (N. p. phaeopus) over a low tide feeding territory. The call is atypical for this bird - it normally does a longer bubbling call which is as yet unrecorded.

The two birds start calling almost in synchrony but the alboaxillaris is the one calling for longer at the end of the recording with the slightly more exagerated note structure.  The N. p. phaeopus is calling similar to the 'whining' call described in BWP.
